    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Chrysanthemoides monilifera</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_9666",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Fairly large shrub growing to at least 3 m and with woody stems becoming green and fleshy distally. Leaves fleshy and pointed with serrated edges, surfaces of young leaves covered in cobweb-like hairs which are lost as they mature. Yellow daisy-like flowers born in groups of about 5. Unusual fleshy fruit are borne in groups and are initially green becoming blackish when mature (hence allusion to ‘ticks’ in the common name)</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_9667",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Plants up to at least 2 m tall, leaves about 45 mm long and 24 mm wide and flowers about 40 mm across.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_9668",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Widespread in Southern and Eastern Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Common not only along the coast, but also far inland including mountain regions.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_9669",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>A very common and well-known species. Can occur right against the coast, on dunes just above the highwater mark, but also widespread in fynbos, grassland and rocky areas and widely grown in gardens. Flowers mainly from March to September and pollinated by a variety of insects. The fruit are sought after by frugivorous birds which play an important role in seed dispersal.</p><p>Has been introduced to Australia and New Zealand to stabilize soils and has now become a serious pest there.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_9670",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_9671",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Flowers throughout the year, but mainly in autumn and winter.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_9672",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Fairly distinctive in both habitat and appearance and best recognised by the unusual fruit. There are several recognised subspecies.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_9673",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
    ],
